Then, the next elements start at j+1 (0-based). So in Fortran, the array is 1-based, so the same logic would be that after j (1-based), the next elements start at j+1 (1-based). So in Fortran, for each i and j, the starting index for the search is j+1. But wait, in the Java code, j runs from i+1 (exclusive) to N-1 (since in Java, indices are 0-based). So in Fortran, when i is from 1 to N-1, j runs from i+1 to N-1 (if 0-based), but in Fortran's 1-based, j runs from i+1 to N.

Wait, let's clarify. In Java code:

for (i=0; i<N; i++) 

   for (j=i+1; j<N; j++)
